1
00:01:04,970 --> 00:01:08,970
- Hold your end up higher.
- I am.

2
00:01:09,060 --> 00:01:11,980
- You are not.
- Don't worry about me.

3
00:01:12,060 --> 00:01:13,650
Mm.

4
00:01:14,440 --> 00:01:17,820
- Hey, isn't that suit charcoal?
- No.

5
00:01:17,900 --> 00:01:22,280
Looks charcoal grey to me.
Some gray polyester blend.

6
00:01:22,360 --> 00:01:26,080
Couldn't you find a black suit
for your father's funeral?

7
00:01:26,160 --> 00:01:27,990
- It's black.
- It's grey.

8
00:01:28,080 --> 00:01:30,290
- It's black. Black.
- Grey. Grey!

9
00:01:30,370 --> 00:01:32,000
Fine, it's black.

10
00:01:33,290 --> 00:01:36,000
It's the greyest black
I've ever seen.

11
00:01:36,090 --> 00:01:38,500
- The colour doesn't matter!
- Oww!

12
00:01:42,170 --> 00:01:44,760
I'm sorry, Pop. I'm sorry!

13
00:01:57,270 --> 00:02:01,740
- Quick! Get him out of there!
- He's halfway to the harbour by now.

14
00:02:01,860 --> 00:02:03,740
Ah, well.

15
00:04:09,030 --> 00:04:12,530
(Man) "I leave you
not just a model factory...

16
00:04:12,620 --> 00:04:17,290
"but something infinitely
more valuable.

17
00:04:17,370 --> 00:04:22,460
"The future of string... itself."

18
00:04:22,540 --> 00:04:24,380
(Explosion, shouting)

19
00:04:31,550 --> 00:04:35,010
"And thus it is my dying wish...

20
00:04:35,100 --> 00:04:39,600
"that my two sons
run Smuntz String together."

21
00:04:39,690 --> 00:04:42,940
Great. Stick a "For Sale" sign up,
see what we can get.

22
00:04:43,020 --> 00:04:46,980
Ernie, we're not supposed to sell it.
We're supposed to run it.

23
00:04:47,070 --> 00:04:51,570
Either way, this godforsaken museum
piece is not worth a dime, is it?

24
00:04:51,660 --> 00:04:55,870
Some things are more important
than money, Ernie.

25
00:04:55,950 --> 00:04:59,000
The financially challenged
always say that.

26
00:04:59,080 --> 00:05:01,290
Uh, please, please.

27
00:05:01,370 --> 00:05:05,460
"I also bequeath to you
my personal effects,

28
00:05:05,540 --> 00:05:09,170
"including my ceramic egg,

29
00:05:12,050 --> 00:05:15,640
"half box of Cuban cigars..."

30
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:18,020
Oh! Yes, yes, yes, yes.

31
00:05:18,100 --> 00:05:22,980
- "M-my collection of spoons."
- (Clattering)

32
00:05:23,770 --> 00:05:27,480
(Ernie) My goodness,
what a treasure. What a legacy.

33
00:05:27,570 --> 00:05:32,610
Spoons! Spoons!
So many spoons, so little time.

34
00:05:32,700 --> 00:05:36,990
Oh! And, of course, something
no household should be without.

35
00:05:37,080 --> 00:05:39,830
The ceramic egg! Ooh-hoo-hoo.

36
00:05:39,910 --> 00:05:42,830
Can I have the egg?
Can I? Huh? Huh?

37
00:05:42,920 --> 00:05:46,340
- No. I want you to have it.
- Fine, I'll take it!

38
00:05:46,460 --> 00:05:50,300
If you find any real estate
on that desk, let me know.

39
00:05:50,380 --> 00:05:52,510
It seems there is also a house.

40
00:05:52,590 --> 00:05:55,510
- (Together) A house?
- Yes, 5120 Nortondale.

41
00:05:55,590 --> 00:06:01,100
Your father acquired it
many years ago as payment of a debt.

42
00:06:01,180 --> 00:06:05,400
H-he never lived there,
but i-i-it's interesting.

43
00:06:05,480 --> 00:06:10,400
It seems the previous owner was found
locked in a trunk in the attic.

44
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:12,900
Wait a minute. Is it worth anything?

45
00:06:12,990 --> 00:06:16,120
Well, he was able to borrow
$50,000 against it.

46
00:06:16,200 --> 00:06:19,910
Really? So, what is its value today?

47
00:06:19,990 --> 00:06:21,950
$50,000.

48
00:06:22,040 --> 00:06:26,630
Great. A worthless house
and a broken-down string factory.

49
00:06:26,710 --> 00:06:30,630
Oh, well. At least the day
wasn't a total loss.

50
00:06:30,710 --> 00:06:33,420
Thanks for the stogies, Pop.

51
00:06:33,510 --> 00:06:37,680
Wait. You can't go. W-we
have to go through all these papers.

52
00:06:42,140 --> 00:06:44,730
You'll have to excuse me.

53
00:06:44,810 --> 00:06:47,650
- I've got a date with the mayor.
- (Thunder rolls)

54
00:06:48,520 --> 00:06:50,070
(Reporters chattering)

55
00:06:51,980 --> 00:06:55,150
Mr Mayor! Mr Mayor, over here!
Mr Mayor!

56
00:06:55,240 --> 00:06:59,240
Will your recent triple heart bypass
affect your campaign strategy?

57
00:06:59,370 --> 00:07:01,620
Now, Leslie, I'm just here to eat.

58
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:06,710
(French accent) Ah, monsieur
le maire, Madame maire,

59
00:07:06,790 --> 00:07:08,420
welcome to Chez Ernie.

60
00:07:08,500 --> 00:07:11,960
What an honour it is
to have you in my humble bistro.

61
00:07:12,050 --> 00:07:16,550
Suivez-moi. You brought the little
ones. The little bicycle thieves.

62
00:07:16,630 --> 00:07:19,390
Bonjour! Our very best table.

63
00:07:19,470 --> 00:07:21,760
- Have you lost weight?
- Oh, I...

64
00:07:21,850 --> 00:07:25,480
- I think so! I think you may be!
- (Laughs)

65
00:07:25,560 --> 00:07:28,230
Je suisse enchanté
pour votre beauté.

66
00:07:28,310 --> 00:07:30,560
- You know?
- Oh, monsieur Ernie...

67
00:07:30,650 --> 00:07:33,780
Excusez-moi. Au revoir, les enfants!

68
00:07:36,780 --> 00:07:40,120
(Sighs)
The air's not so thin at the top.

69
00:07:42,080 --> 00:07:45,250
Just like the old man to die
before I hit it big.

70
00:07:48,250 --> 00:07:52,630
Remember, everyone.
Attention to detail is vital!

71
00:07:52,710 --> 00:07:56,130
Presentation is everything.

72
00:07:57,220 --> 00:08:00,800
No, no, no, no, no!
These I must deliver myself.

73
00:08:00,890 --> 00:08:03,720
(Roars)

74
00:08:10,520 --> 00:08:13,690
Duck a I'Orange
avec du quack sauce...

75
00:08:13,770 --> 00:08:17,610
And for ze Mayor,
la specialite de la maison,

76
00:08:17,690 --> 00:08:20,820
Lobster Loaf a la Ernest
ou la bibliotheque.

77
00:08:20,910 --> 00:08:23,330
- Oh...
- Bon appetit.

78
00:08:23,410 --> 00:08:25,370
(Exhales)

79
00:08:26,950 --> 00:08:29,210
- Ah, bonjour!
- How does it feel...

80
00:08:29,290 --> 00:08:31,880
to serve the mayor
after his re-election?

81
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:35,130
- Well... May I call you Leslie?
- Of course.

82
00:08:39,470 --> 00:08:43,220
Crunchy! Hmm. I love the almonds.

83
00:08:43,300 --> 00:08:46,430
Leslie, cuisine,
she is a fickle mistress...

84
00:08:46,520 --> 00:08:50,560
Ee-yew! Look! (Squishing)

85
00:08:50,690 --> 00:08:52,980
- A cockroach!
- (Shocked whispering)

86
00:08:54,900 --> 00:08:56,900
That's only half a cockroach.

87
00:08:56,980 --> 00:09:00,070
Daddy! You ate the head!

88
00:09:00,150 --> 00:09:02,780
Honey, are you OK?

89
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:15,290
(Screaming)

90
00:09:15,380 --> 00:09:17,590
(Mayor's wife) Not again!

91
00:09:17,670 --> 00:09:20,170
Was this an accident or murder...?

92
00:09:20,260 --> 00:09:21,930
Clear!

93
00:09:23,090 --> 00:09:27,390
- I can do that better!
- (Crying)

94
00:09:34,980 --> 00:09:38,280
(Man) Smuntz String
is a relic of history.

95
00:09:38,360 --> 00:09:43,070
You don't make string by twining
two strands together any more.

96
00:09:43,160 --> 00:09:47,410
No. You make it simple,
singular, strong, with nylon.

97
00:09:47,490 --> 00:09:50,620
Bu-but that's not string.
Tha-that's cord.

98
00:09:50,700 --> 00:09:54,330
- Exactly.
- Twine is yesterday. Cord is today.

99
00:09:54,420 --> 00:09:59,130
Zeppco was interested in your factory
but your father refused to sell.

100
00:09:59,210 --> 00:10:01,170
We are hopin' you're smarter.

101
00:10:01,260 --> 00:10:03,760
Zeppco is willin'
to buy you out...

102
00:10:03,840 --> 00:10:06,970
and bring this museum
into the 21st century.

103
00:10:07,050 --> 00:10:11,730
We'd keep you on as a consultant,
with a huge salary and hefty pension.

104
00:10:13,390 --> 00:10:15,690
So...

105
00:10:15,770 --> 00:10:17,860
what do you say?

106
00:10:21,940 --> 00:10:25,820
(Sighs)

107
00:10:38,540 --> 00:10:42,170
- My sons...
- (Whispers) Ernie.

108
00:10:42,260 --> 00:10:46,720
- Ernie!
- Yeah. Just a sec.

109
00:10:46,800 --> 00:10:51,140
I want you... to have... something.

110
00:10:51,220 --> 00:10:54,560
My most prized possession.

111
00:10:54,640 --> 00:10:58,480
(Sighs) Oh, it's
a piece of st-string.

112
00:10:58,560 --> 00:11:03,070
Not just any string. THE string.

113
00:11:03,150 --> 00:11:08,570
I found it my first day in America.

114
00:11:08,660 --> 00:11:11,910
- What's with the string?
- I've had it 60 years.

115
00:11:11,990 --> 00:11:15,460
Here! I want you two to share it.

116
00:11:15,540 --> 00:11:19,420
Maybe it'll bring you
closer together.

117
00:11:19,500 --> 00:11:23,010
- You haven't talked much lately.
- Yeah.

118
00:11:23,090 --> 00:11:26,760
- Ah! What are you doing?
- I'm breaking it in half.

119
00:11:26,840 --> 00:11:29,800
- No! I want you to share it.
- No?

120
00:11:29,890 --> 00:11:32,930
- Forever.
- Sure, Pop, sure.

121
00:11:33,020 --> 00:11:36,100
You carry it the first 50 years,
I'll take it the next.

122
00:11:36,190 --> 00:11:38,900
- Sure.
- And turn up the morphine drip.

123
00:11:38,980 --> 00:11:41,110
(Father) I heard that.

124
00:11:43,570 --> 00:11:48,110
Promise me...
that you will never sell...

125
00:11:48,200 --> 00:11:51,490
Smuntz String...

126
00:11:51,580 --> 00:11:54,700
to one of those big conglomerates.

127
00:11:54,790 --> 00:11:57,290
Keep it between you.

128
00:11:57,370 --> 00:12:00,710
Brothers. Family.

129
00:12:00,790 --> 00:12:04,710
- Promise.
- I promise, Pop.

130
00:12:04,800 --> 00:12:08,590
- (Lars) I promise.
- So, you were sayin'?

131
00:12:09,760 --> 00:12:11,720
I'll have to pass.

132
00:12:11,800 --> 00:12:13,760
What?

133
00:12:15,560 --> 00:12:19,690
"A world without string is chaos."

134
00:12:21,980 --> 00:12:25,030
For once the Smuntz name
was worth something!

135
00:12:25,110 --> 00:12:27,030
- No, no! Don't!
- Oh!

136
00:12:29,110 --> 00:12:31,370
You... You used to love string!

137
00:12:31,450 --> 00:12:35,830
That was when I was dating
the son of a wealthy string magnate!

138
00:12:35,910 --> 00:12:41,000
Not now, when I am married to the
owner... of a worthless death-trap!

139
00:12:43,540 --> 00:12:47,010
I thought you'd be happy!
I stood up for myself today!

140
00:12:47,090 --> 00:12:49,170
April, I've got new ideas.

141
00:12:49,260 --> 00:12:51,340
You know, I've got big plans!

142
00:12:51,430 --> 00:12:55,510
Don't you see, Lars?
That's all you've ever had are plans.

143
00:12:55,600 --> 00:13:00,440
But my life is passing me by,
and I... I need more!

144
00:13:00,520 --> 00:13:05,400
There's no air in the middle class,
Lars. I can't breathe here.

145
00:13:05,480 --> 00:13:07,860
Please, April, don't go.

146
00:13:07,940 --> 00:13:10,360
I'm not going anywhere.

147
00:13:26,920 --> 00:13:31,260
(TV) 'In a few moments, the joy
of the holidays was shattered...

148
00:13:31,340 --> 00:13:34,010
'and the world changed
for many people.

149
00:13:34,090 --> 00:13:36,350
'Mayor McKrinkle died at 4:30pm,

150
00:13:36,430 --> 00:13:38,720
'at Our Lady of Sorrows Hospital.

151
00:13:38,810 --> 00:13:41,440
'Doctors say
the cause of death is...

152
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:45,270
'heart failure due to
the mayor's culinary disaster.

153
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:47,820
'And once the hottest restaurant...

154
00:13:47,900 --> 00:13:50,860
'Chez Ernie is scheduled
for demolition.'

155
00:13:50,940 --> 00:13:55,160
I-I don't think I ordered
my cheese sandwich with capers.

156
00:13:55,240 --> 00:13:58,290
- 'We go live to Leslie Reinhart.'
- Sorry.

157
00:13:58,370 --> 00:14:01,460
'If this tragedy has a villain
it is Ernie Smuntz.

158
00:14:01,580 --> 00:14:04,250
- 'Once a local... '
- Ernie, you're on TV!

159
00:14:04,330 --> 00:14:06,920
What? Oh.

160
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:09,420
You know what this is? I'll tell ya.

161
00:14:09,510 --> 00:14:12,170
- Guilt by accusation.
- No capers.

162
00:14:12,260 --> 00:14:15,550
But that's just grilled cheese.
What's the point?

163
00:14:15,640 --> 00:14:17,890
Why don't they eat out of a trough?

164
00:14:17,970 --> 00:14:22,180
Which one of you palateless sheep
sent my sandwich back?

165
00:14:22,270 --> 00:14:24,230
Hi, Ernie!

166
00:14:24,310 --> 00:14:25,810
Lars?

167
00:14:27,610 --> 00:14:30,440
(Ernie) When I'm in the kitchen,
I cook.

168
00:14:30,530 --> 00:14:33,070
I can't control everything in there.

169
00:14:33,150 --> 00:14:36,240
(Lars) You know,
it isn't fair to blame you.

170
00:14:36,320 --> 00:14:41,160
- You didn't do anything wrong.
- But society likes to persecute.

171
00:14:41,250 --> 00:14:46,170
A scapegoat, someone to demonise.
The same thing happened to Galileo.

172
00:14:46,250 --> 00:14:49,170
Really? That's unbelievable.

173
00:14:49,250 --> 00:14:51,590
With a cockroach and everything?

174
00:14:51,670 --> 00:14:56,010
No. The point is, I put everything
into that restaurant.

175
00:14:56,090 --> 00:14:58,510
It was my livelihood and my home.

176
00:14:58,600 --> 00:15:01,850
In one fatal bite,
it was all taken away from me.

177
00:15:01,930 --> 00:15:04,060
If only we could sell the factory.

178
00:15:04,140 --> 00:15:09,690
I'd let you stay with me, you know,
but, uh, April threw me out.

179
00:15:09,770 --> 00:15:13,400
- Oh, that's too bad.
- Yeah, well, don't worry about me.

180
00:15:13,490 --> 00:15:16,820
April's been like this
since high school.

181
00:15:16,910 --> 00:15:20,200
- She'll be back. I...
- Would you look at them?

182
00:15:20,280 --> 00:15:24,250
Sleeping in the street. Pitiful.

183
00:15:26,290 --> 00:15:29,080
If I had a house, I'd sleep in it!

184
00:15:29,170 --> 00:15:34,670
- Remember how close we were as kids?
- No.

185
00:15:34,760 --> 00:15:38,260
Hey! Merry Christmas!

186
00:15:38,340 --> 00:15:40,470
Yeah, I was on top once too.

187
00:15:40,550 --> 00:15:45,480
But there's only one way to go from
there, and that's down, baby, down!

188
00:15:45,600 --> 00:15:46,940
Oh!

189
00:15:48,190 --> 00:15:50,110
Ernie.

190
00:15:50,190 --> 00:15:54,320
Ernie! Ernie, there was
a quarter in there.

191
00:15:54,400 --> 00:15:59,110
A quarter? You think so small, Lars.

192
00:15:59,200 --> 00:16:04,080
Look at the bigger picture.
You have no home, no wife, no money.

193
00:16:04,160 --> 00:16:08,000
You have no discernible talents.
How can you ignore that?

194
00:16:08,080 --> 00:16:11,630
Ernie, it's Christmas.

195
00:16:11,710 --> 00:16:15,920
Instead of dwelling on what we lack,
let's be thankful for what we have.

196
00:16:16,010 --> 00:16:22,720
# If only in my dreams #

197
00:17:09,980 --> 00:17:12,150
(Ernie) What a dump.

198
00:17:21,030 --> 00:17:24,780
Wow! I can't believe Pops
never told us about this house.

199
00:17:26,620 --> 00:17:28,620
It's huge.

200
00:17:28,700 --> 00:17:31,420
(Ernie) This is
the kind of house he'd have.

201
00:17:31,500 --> 00:17:34,460
It's just like him. Cold and spooky.

202
00:17:38,760 --> 00:17:43,010
- Wow! Did you feel that?
- What?

203
00:17:43,090 --> 00:17:46,430
I got a chill. You shouldn't
talk about Pop like that.

204
00:17:46,510 --> 00:17:49,310
Really? What's this do for you?

205
00:17:49,390 --> 00:17:54,230
Thanks for nothing,
you string-sucking old loon!

206
00:17:56,860 --> 00:17:59,280
He didn't mean it, Pop.

207
00:18:01,610 --> 00:18:03,990
Ernie! Ernie!

208
00:18:11,710 --> 00:18:15,420
Only one bed.
I'll flip you for it.

209
00:18:17,630 --> 00:18:19,840
Heads.

210
00:18:38,150 --> 00:18:40,320
- (Scratching)
- E-Ernie?

211
00:18:42,070 --> 00:18:45,860
- Ernie. Ernie.
- (Groans)

212
00:18:45,950 --> 00:18:48,700
- You asleep?
- I was.

213
00:18:48,780 --> 00:18:52,080
- (Scratching)
- How can you sleep through that?

214
00:18:52,160 --> 00:18:55,500
- What? I don't hear anything.
- Shh-shh-shh. That.

215
00:18:55,580 --> 00:18:59,170
Listen. Hear it?
It's coming from upstairs.

216
00:18:59,250 --> 00:19:02,420
(Scratching)

217
00:19:03,840 --> 00:19:05,760
(Door creaks)

218
00:19:20,020 --> 00:19:22,150
Mothballs.

219
00:19:24,400 --> 00:19:26,450
(Screaming)

220
00:19:26,530 --> 00:19:29,830
H-hey, stop it! Hey! Ow!

221
00:19:29,950 --> 00:19:31,830
(Grunting)

222
00:19:38,790 --> 00:19:41,340
(Whispering) Ernie! Ernie!

223
00:19:41,420 --> 00:19:43,340
(Groaning)

224
00:19:46,470 --> 00:19:48,930
(Rattling)

225
00:19:51,310 --> 00:19:53,220
(Ernie grunts)

226
00:20:09,700 --> 00:20:11,620
- (Thunderclap)
- (Screaming)

227
00:20:21,290 --> 00:20:23,420
Wait. Wait a minute. Stop. Stop!

228
00:20:23,500 --> 00:20:27,470
Look. Look, look, look.
It's only a toy.

229
00:20:32,300 --> 00:20:34,720
(Screaming)

230
00:20:34,810 --> 00:20:37,430
Ah, shut up!

231
00:20:38,640 --> 00:20:41,480
(Scratching)

232
00:20:43,520 --> 00:20:45,780
It's coming from up there!

233
00:20:48,450 --> 00:20:52,200
One, two, three!

234
00:20:57,080 --> 00:20:58,870
(Panting) Ooh!

235
00:20:59,870 --> 00:21:03,340
- It's just a mouse.
- What?

236
00:21:03,420 --> 00:21:07,550
- It's just a mouse. Never mind.
- (Straining)

237
00:21:07,630 --> 00:21:10,880
Hey, there are some posters up here.

238
00:21:10,970 --> 00:21:14,300
Oh! Stand still!

239
00:21:20,350 --> 00:21:22,350
(Yells)

240
00:21:24,310 --> 00:21:25,820
(Spitting)

241
00:21:27,440 --> 00:21:30,240
- They're blueprints.
- Wow!

242
00:21:30,320 --> 00:21:33,910
Wait a minute.
Look at this date. 1876.

243
